ule seems to be about testing class and file names that don't include a $, so inner classes should be fine, right?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering security manager changes**\\n\\nI'm pondering the removal of the security manager. On JDK 17, it seems custom security managers are allowed with a warning, but when it comes to JDK 21, I think I might need to use `-Djava.security.manager=allow`. If I'm defining a value as a class name, it may enable permissions as well. I'm curious about how these changes might impact security and what it specifically means for permission settings in different contexts.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring JDK security settings**\\n\\nI'm trying to understand the JDK's behavior regarding security settings. It seems that the property value is checked at startup, and I’m wondering if it only allows certain configurations if launched with a specific setting. Setting anything at runtime might be too late. I think it checks the `allowSecurityManager()` system property at each launch. Also, looking into JDK 21, the implications of the security manager scenario from JEP 411 are intriguing.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_aCyyEgbOlElz5UQ2kzTNoDsI|fc_078cdb37dbc42889016a294e8b06f88190abb72c2db1c8d4ab", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "java -version 2>&1 | head -5"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1083, "output": 3354, "cacheRead": 41984, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 46421, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781091894810, "responseId": "resp_078cdb37dbc42889016a294e3766448190909f47a23534266f"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_aCyyEgbOlElz5UQ2kzTNoDsI|fc_078cdb37dbc42889016a294e8b06f88190abb72c2db1c8d4ab", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "java version \"25.0.3\" 2026-04-21 LTS\nJava(TM) SE Runtime